# .cursorrules — Project intelligence and working rules

Purpose: Project-specific working rules for the Cursor agent. These are active guidelines the agent must follow when editing, creating, or suggesting code in this repository.

Key patterns
- Use `UUID` (secure) for all `id` fields: `crypto.randomUUID()` at runtime.
- Use `title: string` for human-visible names on all domain entities.
- Svelte components must follow Svelte 5 idioms (signals, lifecycle updates).
- Main process handles secrets and tokens; renderer never receives raw tokens.

Update triggers (MANDATORY)
1. After any code commit that changes behavior, update `activeContext.md` and `progress.md`.
2. After adding/modifying API endpoints or services, update `systemPatterns.md` and `techContext.md`.
3. After implementing tests or changing dependencies, update `techContext.md` and `progress.md`.

Documentation hygiene
- On every significant change, update `memory-bank/activeContext.md` with the current focus and next steps.
- Summaries should be concise: what changed, why, and next action.

How I (Cursor) will use this file
- Record discovered repo conventions and decisions here so future sessions can pick up work quickly.
- If any memory here becomes incorrect, prefer deleting it and writing the corrected note.


Core rule — Minimal, explicit changes only
- Always generate the minimal code required to satisfy the user's explicit request.
- Do not create new files, types, functions, or large code blocks unless the user explicitly asks for them.
- Prefer editing existing code over adding new files. If a new file is necessary, ask first unless the user explicitly granted permission.
- Avoid speculative implementation: do not implement features, helpers, or APIs that were not requested.

Communication and approvals
- When a change might affect multiple files or require architectural work, present a short plan and request approval before implementing.
- If a change potentially impacts tests, linting, or CI thresholds, mention this upfront and ask whether to proceed.

Testing and safety
- When adding or modifying code, run relevant tests and fix only test files when the user explicitly asks to "only update unit test files".
- Do not relax coverage or lint thresholds unless the user asks.

Documentation and memory
- Do not create or modify memory-bank markdown files unless explicitly requested. If the user requests updates to the memory bank, create or update the appropriate files and include a short summary in the response.

If this rule conflicts with an explicit user instruction, follow the explicit instruction.


